<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 3:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If23402b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I9f85f1c0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>3.</label.designator><headtext>Powers of the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94edd013e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>3:17.</label.designator><headtext>Special court assignment power</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel was directed by Congress in the Regional Rail Reorganization Act of 1973 to assign the members of a special three-judge court to hear matters arising under that statute.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If23429c06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] Pursuant to a request that it do so, the Panel appointed the Special Court[<footnote.reference refid="If23450d16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] and subsequently filled a vacancy on it.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If23450d26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] The special court adopted rules and conducted numerous trials as three-judge courts dealing with railway reorganization. <eos/><bos/>This power represents the first time Congress has delegated any tasks to the Panel not part of its original duties under <cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I551f9bb06b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The assignment of this task to the Panel was a logical one, for the statute required the Panel to order consolidation of proceedings under the statute in a district <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“which the Panel determines to be convenient to the parties and the one most likely to be able to conduct any proceedings under this section with the least delay and the greatest possible fairness and ability.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="If23450d36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] The Panel&apos;s initial decision in this matter reflects a decision of essentially the same nature as other decisions made by it.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If23450d46b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] The special court was abolished in 1996, so this power is of historic interest only.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If23402b16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If23429c06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-serial-number="1974105558" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RS" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I551d2ab16b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">Regional Rail Reorganization Act</cite.query> of 1973, Pub. L. No. 93236, § 209(b), 87 Stat. 985, 999 (1974).<eos/><bos/> The statute appears in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If23450d06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If23450d16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-serial-number="1974105558" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I551d78d16b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">In re Litigation Under Regional Rail Reorganization Act of 1973, 373 F. Supp. 1401 (J.P.M.L. 1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If23450d26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> In re Litigation Under Reg. Rail Reorg. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-serial-number="1975290879" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I551f4d916b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">Act of 1973, 404 F. Supp. 477 (J.P.M.L. 1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If23450d36b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-serial-number="1974105558" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RS" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I55205f016b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">Regional Rail Reorganization Act</cite.query> of 1973, <cite.query w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="SL" w-normalized-cite="I048AF38F71-2C4AAE87385-194BC8CE891" w-pub-number="1077005" ID="I552086126b3e11e9ac68aff86f85b2c9">Pub. L. No. 93-236, § 209(b), 87 Stat. 985</cite.query>, 999 (1974).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If23450d46b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913965" w-serial-number="1974105558" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I5520d4316b3e11e9bfe8894985907fa8">In re Litigation Under Regional Rail Reorganization Act of 1973, 373 F. Supp. 1401 (J.P.M.L. 1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 3:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
